		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">jargon wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Get me both Apple IIe / IIgs BASIC and I will prolly return the favor somehow later on.</div><br />The "Applesoft" BASIC interpreter was developed by Microsoft for Apple. Apple II Plus and older Apple IIe machines had Applesoft 78; machines sold after the introduction of the IIc (such as IIGS and later IIe) had the "enhanced" version that handled lower-case program input correctly.<br /><br />The IIe ROM comes with <a href="http://applewin.berlios.de/" class="postlink">AppleWin</a>, and the IIGS ROM is on this <a href="http://emulation.victoly.com/apple2/" class="postlink">list of Apple II series emulators that run on various versions of Mac OS</a>. To verify whether your ROM has an "enhanced" BASIC or not: start your emulator, turn off caps lock, get a ] prompt, and try doing<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">10 print n$<br />list</div><br />If you successfully get all caps like this:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp;10&nbsp; PRINT N$<br /><br />&#93;</div><br />then you have an enhanced BASIC.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">jargon wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">MISHAP does for text adventures what SCUMM did for graphical adventures.</div>
<br />I think you mean <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-machine#Frotz" class="postlink">Frotz</a> <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";-)" title="Wink" />

		

		</td>
	</tr>
